]] (attended 1895-1896)\n* [[George Rupp]]\n* Father [[V.C. Samuel]] (PhD. 1957) Indian Christian Theologian and Historian.\n* [[Ron Sider]]\n* [[John Silber]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n* [[John Shelby Spong]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n* [[Amos Alonzo Stagg]]\n* [[Barbara Brown Taylor]] (M.Div. 1976)\n* [[Roy M. Terry]] (B.D. 1942)\n* [[Krista Tippett]] (M.Div. 1994)\n* [[R. A. Torrey]] (B.D. 1878)\n* [[John W. Traphagan]] (M.A.R. 1986), professor of Religious Studies and Anthropology, [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n* [[Glenn M. Wagner]] (M.Div. 1978)\n* [[Chester Wickwire]] (B.D. 1946)\n* [[Parker T. Williamson]] (M.Phil.)\n* [[William Willimon]] (M.Div. 1971)\n\n==Notable past professors==\n=== Former Faculty: 20th-21st Century ===\n\n*[[Roland Bainton]]\n*[[Brevard Childs]]\n*[[Rebecca Chopp]]\n*[[Adela Yarbro Collins]], 2000\u20132015\n*[[Jerome Davis (sociologist)|Jerome Davis]]\n*[[Margaret Farley]]\n*[[Hans Wilhelm Frei]]\n*[[Paul L. Holmer]]\n*[[Serene Jones]]\n*[[David Kelsey]]\n*[[Kenneth Scott Latourette]]\n*[[George Lindbeck]]\n*[[Sallie McFague]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n*[[Douglas Clyde Macintosh]]\n*[[Reinhold Niebuhr]]\n*[[H. Richard Niebuhr]]\n*[[Henri Nouwen]], 1971\u20131981\n*[[Liston Pope]] (Dean)\n*[[Letty M. Russell]] (1974\u20132001)\n*[[Lamin Sanneh]]\n*[[Emilie Townes]]\n*[[Denys Turner]]\n*[[Nicholas Wolterstorff]]\n*[[Henry Burt Wright]] (1877-1923)\n\n=== Former Faculty: 19th Century ===\n\n*[[Lyman Beecher]]\n*[[George Park Fisher]]\n\n== Current faculty (ca. 2019) ==\n\n*[[Harold W. Attridge]]\n*Teresa Berger\n*[[John J. Collins]]\n*Michal Beth Dinkler\n*[[John E. Hare]]\n*Erika Helgen\n*Jennifer A. Herdt\n*[[Willie James Jennings]]\n*Yii-Jan Lin\n*Eboni Marshall Turman\n*Donyelle McCray\n*[[Andrew McGowan]]\n*Joyce Mercer\n*Mary Clark Moschella\n*Laura Nasrallah\n*Sally M. Promey\n*Melanie Ross\n*Janet Ruffing\n*Carolyn J. Sharp\n*Chlo\u00eb Starr\n*[[Kathryn Tanner]]\n*Gabrielle Thomas\n*Linn Tonstad\n*Jacqueline Vayntrub\n*[[Miroslav Volf]]\n*Tisa Wenger\n*[[Christian Wiman]]\n*Almeda M. Wright\n\n==See also==\n* [[General Theological Seminary]], a separate New Haven institution now located in New York City\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://divinity.yale.edu Yale Divinity School website]\n* [http://berkeleydivinity.net Berkeley Divinity School at Yale]\n* [https://divinity.yale.edu/admissions-aid/degree-programs-and-certificates/andover-newton-seminary-yale Andover Newton Seminary at Yale]\n\n{{Yale}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Religion and science]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1822]]\n[[Category:1822 establishments in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Yale Divinity School| ]]\n[[Category:Seminaries and theological colleges in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Yale University schools|Divinity School]]\n[[Category:Christian seminaries and theological colleges]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = Yale Divinity School\n| type = Private\n| parent = [[Yale University]]\n| image_name = File:Yale Divinity School.png\n| image_size = 150px\n| image_alt = [[Coat of arms]] of the school, containing a book device inscribed with Hebrew letters and cross in front of a red background\n| caption = [[Coat of arms]] of the school<br />with the university's ''[[Urim and Thummim|Urim V'Thummim]]'' motto under a [[Christian cross|cross]] and halo\n| established = {{Start date|1822}}\n| city = [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]]\n| state = [[Connecticut]]\n| country = U.S.\n| coor = {{Coord|41|19|24|N|72|55|17|W|region:US_type:edu|display=title}}\n| dean = Gregory E. Sterling\n| faculty = \n| students = 392<ref>{{cite web| title=YDS at a Glance |publisher=Yale Divinity School |url=http://divinity.yale.edu/admissions/yds-glance |accessdate=9 March 2014}}</ref>\n| website = {{url|divinity.yale.edu}}\n}}\n\nThe '''School of Divinity''' at [[Yale University]], in [[New Haven]], [[Connecticut]], is one of twelve graduate or professional schools within Yale University.\n\n[[Congregational church|Congregationalist]] theological education was the motivation at the founding of Yale, and the professional school has its roots in a Theological Department established in 1822. The school had maintained its own campus, faculty, and degree program since 1869, and it has become more ecumenical beginning in the mid-19th century. Since the 1970s, it has been affiliated with the [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]] [[Berkeley Divinity School]] and has housed the [[Yale Institute of Sacred Music|Institute of Sacred Music]], which offers separate degree programs. In July 2017, a two-year process of formal affiliation was completed, with the addition of [[Andover Newton Seminary at Yale Divinity School|Andover Newton Seminary]] joining the school.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Divinity College at Yale before 1870, Memories of Yale life and men, 1854-1899 (1903).jpg|thumb|200px|The Divinity College dormitory on the [[Old Campus (Yale University)|Old Campus]], completed in 1836]]\nTheological education was the earliest academic purpose of Yale University. When [[Yale College]] was founded in 1701, it was as a college of religious training for [[Congregationalist]] ministers in [[Connecticut Colony]], designated in its charter as a school \"wherein Youth may be instructed in the Arts & Sciences who through the blessing of Almighty God may be fitted for Publick employment both in Church & Civil State.\"  A professorship of divinity was established in 1746. In 1817, the occupant of the divinity chair, [[Eleazar Thompson Fitch]], supported a student request to endow a theological curriculum, and five years later a separate {{nowrap|'''Yale Theological Seminary'''}}<ref>{{citation |title=History of Higher Education Annual: 1997 |p=[https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=vgQaGJt9OTQC&pg=PA94 94] }}.</ref> was founded by the [[Yale Corporation]].<ref name=\"Catalogue\">{{cite book |title=A General Catalogue of the Divinity School of Yale College: A Brief Biographical Record of Its Members in The First Half Century of Its Existence as A Distinct Department |url=https://archive.org/details/generalcatalogue00yalerich |publisher=Tuttle, Morehouse, & Taylor |year=1873 |location=New Haven}}</ref> In the same motion, [[Second Great Awakening]] theologian [[Nathaniel William Taylor]] was appointed to become the first Dwight Professor of Didactic Theology.<ref name=\"YUL\">{{cite web |title=Yale Divinity School Milestones, 1822-2012 |publisher=Yale University Library |date=23 October 2012 |url=http://divinity-adhoc.library.yale.edu/Exhibits/YDSMilestones.htm |accessdate=16 November 2015}}</ref> Taylor was considered the \"central figure\" in the school's founding, and he was joined in 1826 by [[Josiah Willard Gibbs, Sr.]], a scholar of sacred languages and lexicographer [[Chauncey A. Goodrich]] in 1839.<ref name=\"YUL\"/> A dedicated student dormitory, Divinity College, was completed on the college's [[Old Campus (Yale University)|Old Campus]] in 1836, but the department had no permanent classrooms or offices until several years after the end of the [[American Civil War]].\n\n[[File:Old Divinity School, Yale University, New Haven, Conn.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Divinity Hall, occupied from 1870 to 1931, viewed from the [[New Haven Green]].]]\nAfter a significant period of enrollment decline, the school began fundraising from alumni for new faculty and facilities.<ref name=\"YUL\"/> Divinity Hall was constructed on the present-day site of [[Calhoun College|Grace Hopper College]] between 1869 and 1871, featuring two classroom wings and a chapel.<ref name=\"YUL\"/>  Around the time of the new campus' construction came the arrival of new faculty, including [[James M. Hoppin]], [[George Edward Day (language scholar)|George Edward Day]], [[George Park Fisher]], and [[Leonard Bacon]].<ref name=\"YUL\"/> The first Bachelor of Divinity (B.D.) was conferred in 1867, and the department became a separate School of Divinity in 1869.<ref name=\"Catalogue\"/> The school remained across from Old Campus until 1929, when a new campus was constructed on the northern edge of the university campus, at the top of [[Prospect Hill, New Haven|Prospect Hill]].\n\n[[Berkeley Divinity School]] affiliated with Yale Divinity School in 1971, and in the same year the university replaced the B.D. with a [[Master of Divinity]] program.  While Berkeley retains its [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopal Church]] connection, its students are admitted by and fully enrolled as members of Yale Divinity School. [[The Jonathan Edwards Center at Yale University]], a division of the Divinity School, maintains a large collection of primary source materials about [[Jonathan Edwards (theologian)|Jonathan Edwards]], a 1720 Yale alumnus. The Yale Institute of Sacred Music (ISM) is jointly-affiliated with the Divinity School and School of Music. It offers programs in choral conducting, organ performance, voice, and church music studies, and in liturgical studies and religion and the arts.\n\nIn May 2016, [[Andover Newton Theological School]] president [[Martin Copenhaver]] announced that Andover Newton would begin a process of formal affiliation with the Divinity School over the next two years. In the 2016\u201317 academic year, a cohort of faculty relocated to New Haven teaching students and launching pilot initiatives focused on congregational ministry education, while Andover Newton continued to operate in Massachusetts over the next two years. In July 2017, a formal affiliation was signed, resulting in smaller Andover Newton functioning as a unit within Yale Divinity School, similar to its arrangement with Berkeley.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://divinity.yale.edu/news/yds-and-andover-newton-sign-historic-agreement|title=YDS and Andover Newton sign historic agreement|date=July 20, 2017|website=Yale Divinity School}}</ref>\n\n== Leadership ==\n[[Gregory E. Sterling]], a New Testament scholar and [[Churches of Christ|Church of Christ]] pastor, has been the dean of the divinity school since 2012, succeeding New Testament scholar [[Harold W. Attridge]], who returned to teaching as a [[Sterling Professor]] upon completing two five-year terms as dean.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://divinity.yale.edu/news/yds-dean-greg-sterling-reappointed-second-five-year-term|title=YDS Dean Greg Sterling reappointed to second five-year term {{!}} Yale Divinity School|website=divinity.yale.edu|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref> The leaders of the affiliated seminaries are [[Andrew McGowan]], Dean and President of Berkeley Divinity School, and Sarah Drummond, Founding Dean of Andover Newton Seminary at Yale Divinity School. Organist [[Martin Jean]] is director of the Institute of Sacred Music.\n\n=== Deans of Yale Divinity School ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Name\n!Years Served\n!Academic Field\n!Denomination\n|-\n|Gregory E. Sterling<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://divinity-adhoc.library.yale.edu/Exhibits/YDSMilestones.htm|title=Yale Divinity Library Exhibit: YDS Milestones 1822-2012|website=divinity-adhoc.library.yale.edu|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n|2012\u2013Present\n|New Testament\n|Churches of Christ\n|-\n|Harold W. Attridge\n|2002-2012\n|New Testament\n|Catholic\n|-\n|[[Rebecca Chopp]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yale.edu/2001/03/19/yale-university-appoints-new-dean-lead-divinity-school|title=Yale University Appoints New Dean to Lead Divinity School|date=2001-03-19|website=YaleNews|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n|2001-2002\n|Theology\n|Methodist\n|-\n|[[Harry B. Adams]] (acting dean)\n|2000-2001\n|Pastoral Theology\n|\n|-\n|Richard J. Wood<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://divinity.yale.edu/news/former-yds-dean-richard-wood-dies-78|title=Former YDS dean Richard Wood dies at 78 {{!}} Yale Divinity School|website=divinity.yale.edu|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-xpm-1996-03-27-9603270433-story.html|title=YALE DIVINITY NAMES NEW DEAN|last=Taylor|first=Frances Grandy|website=Hartford Courant|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n|1996-2000\n|Philosophy\n|Quaker\n|-\n|[[Thomas Ogletree]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://divinity.yale.edu/faculty-and-research/yds-faculty/thomas-w-ogletree|title=Thomas W. Ogletree {{!}} Yale Divinity School|website=divinity.yale.edu|language=en|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n|1990-1996\n|Ethics\n|Methodist\n|-\n|[[Aidan Kavanagh]] (acting dean)\n|1989-1990\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Leander Keck]]\n|1979-1989\n|New Testament\n|Christian Church (Disciples of Christ)\n|-\n|[[Colin W. Williams]]\n|1969-1979\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Robert Clyde Johnson]]\n|1963-1969\n|\n|\n|-\n|Charles Forman (acting dean)\n|1961-1963\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Liston Pope]]\n|1949-1962\n|Ethics\n|Congregationalist\n|-\n|[[Luther Allan Weigle]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biola.edu/talbot/ce20/database/luther-allan-weigle|title=Luther Allan Weigle|website=Database: Christian Educators of the 20th Century|publisher=Biola University|language=en-us|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n|1928-1949\n|Christian Education\n|Lutheran/Congregationalist\n|-\n|[[Charles Reynolds Brown]]\n|1911-1928\n|Theology\n|Congregationalist\n|-\n|[[Edward Lewis Curtis]] (acting dean)\n|1905-1911\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Frank Knight Sanders]]\n|1901-1905\n|Semitics\n|Congregationalist\n|-\n|[[George Park Fisher]]\n|1895-1901\n|Church History\n|Congregationalist\n|-\n|George Edward Day<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.library.yale.edu/divinity/day-missions-library|title=Day Missions Library {{!}} Yale University Library|website=web.library.yale.edu|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>\n|1888-1895\n|Hebrew\n|Congregationalist\n|}\n\n*\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:Yale Divinity School Highsmith.jpg|thumb|Sterling Divinity Quadrangle, campus of the Yale Divinity School]]\nWhen the department was organized as a school in 1869, it was moved to a campus across from the northwest corner of the [[New Haven Green]] composed of East Divinity Hall (1869), Marquand Chapel (1871), West Divinity Hall (1871), and the Trowbridge Library (1881). The buildings, designed by [[Richard Morris Hunt]], were demolished under the [[residential colleges of Yale University|residential college plan]] and replaced by [[Calhoun College|Calhoun College, now known as Grace Hopper College]].<ref>[http://www.yalealumnimagazine.com/issues/01_03/popup/landmarks/12.html Yale's Lost Landmarks: Divinity Hall, Yale Alumni Magazine]</ref>\n\nIn 1929, the trustees of the estate of lawyer [[John William Sterling]] agreed that a portion of his bequest to Yale would be used to build a new campus for the Divinity School.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bedford |first=Steven |title=John Russell Popoe: Architect of Empire |publisher=Random House |location=New York |year=1998 |isbn=9780847820863 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/johnrussellpopea00bedf/page/166 166\u2013168] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/johnrussellpopea00bedf/page/166 }}</ref> The Sterling Divinity Quadrangle, completed in 1932, is a [[Georgian architecture|Georgian]]-style complex built at the top of [[Prospect Hill (New Haven)|Prospect Hill]]. It was designed by [[Delano & Aldrich]] and modeled in part on the [[University of Virginia]].\n\nA $49-million renovation of Sterling Divinity Quadrangle was completed in 2003.\n\n==Notable alumni==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=March 2009}}\n* [[Diogenes Allen]] (B.D. 1959)\n* [[Ian Barbour]] (B.D. 1956)\n* [[Gregory A. Boyd]] (M.Div. 1982)\n* [[Will Campbell (Baptist minister)|Will D. Campbell]] (B.D. 1952)\n* [[Orishatukeh Faduma]] (B.D. 1894, graduate study 1895)\n* [[William Ragsdale Cannon]] (B.D. 1940; Ph.D. 1942), Professor and Dean, [[Candler School of Theology]]; [[Bishop]] of the [[United Methodist Church]].\n* [[Donald Eric Capps]], ([[Bachelor of Divinity|B.D.]] 1963; S.T.M., 1965), scholar of Pastoral Theology\n* [[Roy Clyde Clark]], (B.D. 1944), [[Bishop]] of the [[United Methodist Church]]\n* [[William Sloane Coffin]] (B.D. 1956)\n* [[Chris Coons]] (Master's degree in ethics, 1992), [[United States Senator]] from Delaware\n* [[Harvey Cox]] (B.D. 1955), theologian and [[Hollis Professor of Divinity]] at [[Harvard Divinity School]] (1965\u20132009)\n* [[Raymond Culver]], (B.D. 1920), president of [[Shimer College]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://mssa.library.yale.edu/obituary_record/1925_1952/1937-38.pdf|year=1938|publisher=Yale University|chapter=Raymond Benjamin Culver|title=1937-1938 Obituary Record of Graduates of Yale University|pages=137\u2013138}}</ref>\n* [[Michael Curry (bishop)|Michael Curry]] (M.Div. 1978), Presiding Bishop of the [[Episcopal Church (United States)]]\n* [[John Danforth]] (M.Div. 1963), former [[United States Senator]] from Missouri\n* [[Walter Fauntroy]], (B.D. 1958), Founding Member - [[Congressional Black Caucus]]\n* [[David F. Ford]] (S.T.M.), [[Regius Professor of Divinity]] Emeritus at the [[University of Cambridge]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://polycarp.divinity.cam.ac.uk/faculty/ford.html |title=Faculty Members: Professor David Ford |publisher=University of Cambridge |year=2011 |accessdate=23 May 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Paul Vernon Galloway]], a Bishop of [[The Methodist Church (USA)|The Methodist Church]]\n*[[Tom Vaughn (musician)|Tom Vaughn]] (Doctorate in theology), jazz musician and Episcopal priest\n* [[Leroy Gilbert]] (S.T.M. 1979)\n* [[Gary Hart]] (B.D. 1961)\n* [[Stanley Hauerwas]] (B.D. 1965)\n* [[Richard B. Hays]] (M.Div. 1977)\n* [[Sen Katayama]]\n* [[Ernest W. Lefever]] (1945), foreign affairs expert and founder of the [[Ethics and Public Policy Center]].<ref>Bernstein, Adam. [http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-ernest-lefever31-2009jul31,0,302539.story \"Ernest W. Lefever dies at 89; founder of conservative public policy organization\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', July 31, 2009. Accessed August 3, 2009.</ref>\n*[[Sallie McFague]] (B.D. 1959)\n* [[Candida Moss]] (M.A.R. 2002)\n* [[Otis Moss III]] (M.Div. 1995), Pastor of Trinity Church, Chicago\n* [[Reinhold Niebuhr]] (B.D. 1914, M.A. 1915), Protestant theologian and public intellectual<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kinginstitute.stanford.edu/encyclopedia/niebuhr-reinhold |title=Niebuhr, Reinhold |publisher=The Martin Luther King, Jr. Research and Education Institute |accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Richard T. Nolan]] (M.A. 1967)\n* [[Douglas Oldenburg]] (S.T.M. 1961), President Emeritus at [[Columbia Theological Seminary]], Presbyterian (USA) pastor.\n* [[Julie Faith Parker]]\n* [[William H. Poteat]] (B.D. 1944)\n* [[Clark V. Poling]] (1936)\n* [[Peter L. Pond]], human rights activist and philanthropist.<ref>Mooney, Tom, \"Peter Pond's War,\" Providence Journal, Oct 15, 1989 p. M-06.</ref>\n* [[Adam Clayton Powell, Sr.]] (attended 1895-1896)\n* [[George Rupp]]\n* Father [[V.C. Samuel]] (PhD. 1957) Indian Christian Theologian and Historian.\n* [[Ron Sider]]\n* [[John Silber]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n* [[John Shelby Spong]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n* [[Amos Alonzo Stagg]]\n* [[Barbara Brown Taylor]] (M.Div. 1976)\n* [[Roy M. Terry]] (B.D. 1942)\n* [[Krista Tippett]] (M.Div. 1994)\n* [[R. A. Torrey]] (B.D. 1878)\n* [[John W. Traphagan]] (M.A.R. 1986), professor of Religious Studies and Anthropology, [[University of Texas at Austin]]\n* [[Glenn M. Wagner]] (M.Div. 1978)\n* [[Chester Wickwire]] (B.D. 1946)\n* [[Parker T. Williamson]] (M.Phil.)\n* [[William Willimon]] (M.Div. 1971)\n\n==Notable past professors==\n=== Former Faculty: 20th-21st Century ===\n\n*[[Roland Bainton]]\n*[[Brevard Childs]]\n*[[Rebecca Chopp]]\n*[[Adela Yarbro Collins]], 2000\u20132015\n*[[Jerome Davis (sociologist)|Jerome Davis]]\n*[[Margaret Farley]]\n*[[Hans Wilhelm Frei]]\n*[[Paul L. Holmer]]\n*[[Serene Jones]]\n*[[David Kelsey]]\n*[[Kenneth Scott Latourette]]\n*[[George Lindbeck]]\n*[[Sallie McFague]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n*[[Douglas Clyde Macintosh]]\n*[[Reinhold Niebuhr]]\n*[[H. Richard Niebuhr]]\n*[[Henri Nouwen]], 1971\u20131981\n*[[Liston Pope]] (Dean)\n*[[Letty M. Russell]] (1974\u20132001)\n*[[Lamin Sanneh]]\n*[[Emilie Townes]]\n*[[Denys Turner]]\n*[[Nicholas Wolterstorff]]\n*[[Henry Burt Wright]] (1877-1923)\n\n=== Former Faculty: 19th Century ===\n\n*[[Lyman Beecher]]\n*[[George Park Fisher]]\n\n== Current faculty (ca. 2019) ==\n\n*[[Harold W. Attridge]]\n*Teresa Berger\n*[[John J. Collins]]\n*Michal Beth Dinkler\n*[[John E. Hare]]\n*Erika Helgen\n*Jennifer A. Herdt\n*[[Willie James Jennings]]\n*Yii-Jan Lin\n*Eboni Marshall Turman\n*Donyelle McCray\n*[[Andrew McGowan]]\n*Joyce Mercer\n*Mary Clark Moschella\n*Laura Nasrallah\n*Sally M. Promey\n*Melanie Ross\n*Janet Ruffing\n*Carolyn J. Sharp\n*Chlo\u00eb Starr\n*[[Kathryn Tanner]]\n*Gabrielle Thomas\n*Linn Tonstad\n*Jacqueline Vayntrub\n*[[Miroslav Volf]]\n*Tisa Wenger\n*[[Christian Wiman]]\n*Almeda M. Wright\n\n==See also==\n* [[General Theological Seminary]], a separate New Haven institution now located in New York City\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://divinity.yale.edu Yale Divinity School website]\n* [http://berkeleydivinity.net Berkeley Divinity School at Yale]\n* [https://divinity.yale.edu/admissions-aid/degree-programs-and-certificates/andover-newton-seminary-yale Andover Newton Seminary at Yale]\n\n{{Yale}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Religion and science]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1822]]\n[[Category:1822 establishments in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Yale Divinity School| ]]\n[[Category:Seminaries and theological colleges in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Yale University schools|Divinity School]]\n[[Category:Christian seminaries and theological colleges]]\n", "name_user": "HOUYIMIN", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a photo of quad", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yale_Divinity_School"}
{"title_page": "Tommy Chong", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian-American comedian, actor, and activist}}\n<!--Note:  There is an internet hoax reporting Chong's death.  http://en.mediamass.net/people/tommy-chong/deathhoax.html-->\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name         = Tommy Chong\n| image        = Tommy_Chong_at_Hash_Bash.jpg\n| caption      = Chong in 2015\n| birth_name   = Thomas Bee Kin Chong\n| nationality  = Canadian \u2022 American\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1938|5|24}}  \n| birth_place  = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| medium       = [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], [[film]], [[television]]\n| genre        =  [[Observational comedy]], [[stoner comedy]], [[sketch comedy]], [[satire]]\n| subject      = [[Canadian culture]], [[recreational drug use]], [[drug culture]], [[everyday life]]\n| active       = 1962\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Maxine Sneed|1960|1970|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|[[Shelby Chong|Shelby Fiddis]]|1975}}\n| children     = 5, including [[Rae Dawn Chong|Rae Dawn]], [[Robbi Chong|Robbi]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Bing Kin Chong'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.post-gazette.com/localnews/20030912chong0912p5.asp |website=Post Gazette |title=Actor Tommy Chong gets nine months for selling pot pipes |date=September 12, 2003 |access-date=August 10, 2016 |last=Ove |first=Torsten |publisher=PG Publishing Co., Inc. |quote=Chong, whose full name is Thomas B. Kin Chong,... |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716002912/http://old.post-gazette.com/localnews/20030912chong0912p5.asp |archivedate=July 16, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> (born May 24, 1938) is a Canadian actor, writer, director, musician, [[cannabis rights]] activist and comedian. He is known for his [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]]-themed [[Cheech & Chong]] comedy albums and movies with [[Cheech Marin]], as well as playing the character [[Leo (That '70s Show)|Leo]] on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s ''[[That '70s Show]]''. He became a naturalized United States citizen in the late 1980s.\n\n==Early life==\nThomas B. Kin Chong<ref name= \"nardwuar\">{{cite web |date=August 20, 1993|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bGhBodZP1Jw|title=Nardwuar vs. Tommy Chong|work=Nardwuar | via=YouTube |accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cheechandchong.com/biography.html | title= Bio > Tommy Chong| work= CheechandChong.com (official site)| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120213175242/http://www.cheechandchong.com/bio | archivedate= February 13, 2012}} Note: Tommy Chong bio appears under a different person's section, Shelby Chong.</ref> was born on May 24, 1938 at the [[University of Alberta Hospital]] in [[Edmonton]], Alberta.<ref name=filmref /> His mother was Lorna Jean (n\u00e9e Gilchrist),<ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/18/Tommy-Chong.html | title=Tommy Chong Biography (1938-)| website= FilmReference.com | accessdate= June 17, 2015}}</ref> a waitress of [[Scottish- Canadians|Scottish-Irish]] ancestry,<ref>{{cite news |title= [Unknown title] |volume= 80 |year=1972 |work= [[Newsweek]] |location=|isbn= |page= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=d03uAAAAMAAJ&q=TOMMY+CHONG+SCOTCH+FRENCH&dq=TOMMY+CHONG+SCOTCH+FRENCH |accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref> and his father was Stanley Chong, a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] truck driver who [[Chinese Canadians|immigrated to Canada]] in the 1930s.<ref name= filmref /><ref name=\"asianweek\"/> After arriving in Canada, the senior Chong had first lived with an aunt in [[Vancouver]], where Chinese immigrants were mostly sequestered in a small area due to racial discrimination.<ref name=\"asianweek\">{{cite news | first=Pratt | last=Paul | title=Growing Up a Chong | date=November 18, 2005 | work=AsianWeek | url=http://www.asianweek.com/2005/11/18/growing-up-a-chong/ | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609190311/http://www.asianweek.com/2005/11/18/growing-up-a-chong/ | archivedate=June 9, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=http://norml.org/index.cfm?Group_ID=7072|title= Working to Reform Marijuana Laws | website= NORML.org |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.yahoo.com/thomas-chong/contributor/264446|title=Tommy Chong|work=Yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\nAs a youth, Tommy Chong moved with his family to [[Calgary]], settling in a conservative neighbourhood Chong has referred to as \"Dog Patch\". He has said that his father had \"been wounded in [[World War II]] and there was a veterans' hospital in Calgary. He bought a $500 house in Dog Patch and raised his family on $50 a week.\"<ref name=\"nardwuar\"/> In an interview, Chong later said:\n{{cquote|I dropped out of [[Crescent Heights High School (Calgary, Alberta)|Crescent Heights High School]] when I was 16 but probably just before they were going to throw me out anyway&nbsp;... I played guitar to make money. I was about 16 when I discovered that music could get you [[sexual intercourse|laid]], even if you were a scrawny, long-haired, geeky-looking guy like me.<ref name=\"nardwuar\"/>}}\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nBy the early 1960s, Chong was playing guitar for a Calgary soul group called the Shades. The Shades moved to [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], where the band's name changed to \"Little Daddy & the Bachelors\". They recorded a single, \"Too Much Monkey Business\" / \"Junior's Jerk\". Together with bandmember Bobby Taylor, Chong opened a Vancouver nightclub in 1963.  Formerly the Alma Theatre, they called it \"Blue Balls\". They brought in the [[Ike & Tina Turner]] Revue, which had never been to Vancouver before. Although Little Daddy & the Bachelors built up a small following, things soured when they went with Chong's suggestion and had themselves billed as \"Four [[Nigger]]s and a [[Chink]]\"<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|author=Hamilton, Andrew|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/p130602|title=Bobby Taylor|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> (or, bowing to pressure, \"Four N's and a C\") before taking on the moniker [[Bobby Taylor & the Vancouvers]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n\nIn 1965, the Vancouvers signed with Gordy Records (a subsidiary of Detroit's [[Motown Records]]). They recorded their debut album, an [[eponymous]] release, and their debut single, the Tommy Chong co-composition, \"Does Your Mama Know About Me,\" which peaked at number 29 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> While on tour in Chicago for a short time, the band followed opening act [[the Jackson 5]]. Chong later referred to the young [[Michael Jackson]] as a \"cute little guy\".<ref name=\"tomgreen.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tomgreen.com/?video=1089|title=Tom Green - The Channel - WebovisionTom Green - The Channel|publisher=}}</ref> After the band released two additional singles, Chong and bandmate Wes Henderson missed a Friday night performance to apply for [[Permanent residence (United States)|green cards]] so they could become American citizens. Chong was fired by [[Chris Clark (singer)|Chris Clark]] and Motown producer [[Johnny Bristol]] for arriving late to the gig. Later, when Berry Gordy told Chong that he wasn't fired after all, that it had been a mistake, Chong said he wanted to stay fired. \"I said I want to become a Berry Gordy, I don't want to just work for a Berry Gordy. And he says I can, I can dig that. So he was nice. He gave me $5,000 as the severance and to me that was a fortune.\" - Tommy Chong. <!--Above material apparently had been copied from article \"Bobby Taylor & the Vancouvers\"--><ref name=\"harp\">{{cite web\n |year=2007 \n |url=http://www.harpmagazine.com/articles/detail.cfm?article_id=6162 \n |last=Kayce \n |first=Aaron \n |title=Tommy Chong: From Guitar to Bong \n |work=Harp \n |publisher=HarpMagazine.com \n |accessdate=September 24, 2007 \n |url-status=bot: unknown \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425165739/http://www.harpmagazine.com/articles/detail.cfm?article_id=6162 \n |archivedate=April 25, 2009 \n}}</ref> The group broke up shortly afterwards, when Chong tried to reduce the number of players covered by the Vancouvers' contract. He intended that he, Taylor, and Henderson would constitute the group, while other members would be classified as sidemen and session artists.\n\n===Cheech & Chong===\n{{Main|Cheech & Chong}}\nChong co-wrote and performed on many Cheech & Chong comedy albums, four of which were nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album]]. He and [[Cheech Marin]] shared the 1973 award in this category for ''[[Los Cochinos]]''.<ref>[https://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=%22cheech+and+chong%22&field_nominee_work_value=&year=All&genre=All Cheech and Chong at grammy.com]</ref>\n\nHe also directed four of the duo's films, while co-writing and starring in all seven with Cheech.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Tommy Chong|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/person/683301/Tommy-Chong/filmography}}</ref>\n\n===After Cheech & Chong===\n[[File:Tommy Chong in 2008.jpg|thumb|Chong speaking in San Francisco in 2008.]]\nCheech & Chong, while a very successful comedy act, split in 1985 due to creative differences and Marin's desire to focus on a mainstream acting career. This began a difficult time for Chong. He developed an unsold pilot for CBS called ''The Martinez Family'', which was redeveloped as the 1988 sitcom ''[[Trial and Error (TV series)|Trial and Error]]''.<ref name=\"Irvin2013\">{{cite book|author=Richard Irvin|title=Forgotten Laughs: An Episode Guide to 150 TV Sitcoms You Probably Never Saw|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GqRWDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT276|year=2013|publisher=BearManor Media|pages=276\u2013|id=GGKEY:Y33N3H4NXN4}}</ref> In 1990, he directed, wrote and starred in the movie ''[[Far Out Man]]''. He did not act regularly until filling the recurring role (later a regular role) as the fun-loving, aging hippie \"[[Leo (That '70s Show)|Leo]]\" (similar to his Chong character) on ''[[That '70s Show]]''. Chong was absent during the fifth and sixth seasons of the show as he was serving a brief jail sentence; upon his release, he returned to the series for its final two seasons. He also played a role as a hippie in ''[[Dharma and Greg]]''.\n\nChong was originally going to voice the character of [[Shenzi, Banzai and Ed|Shenzi]], the hyena in the Disney film ''[[The Lion King]]''.{{citation needed| date=May 2018}} Cheech Marin voiced Banzai. (The Shenzi character was changed to a female, and voiced instead by [[Whoopi Goldberg]].) Chong provided the voice of the character Yax in the 2016 Disney film ''[[Zootopia]]''.<ref name=\"USA Today 25 October 2015\">{{cite news | title= J.K. Simmons, Tommy Chong get run of 'Zootopia'|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/10/25/zootopia-jk-simmons-tommy-chong/74369682/| last= Alexander | first= Bryan | date=October 25, 2015| work= USA Today |publisher= [[Gannett Company]]| accessdate= May 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2005, ''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]]'' premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]. The documentary, produced, written and directed by Josh Gilbert, chronicles Chong's comedic and personal history. It includes material related to his prosecution by the [[United States Department of Justice|US Justice Department]] and imprisonment. The project features interviews with Cheech Marin, [[Bill Maher]], [[George Thorogood]], [[Peter Coyote]], [[Lou Adler]], [[Eric Schlosser]] and [[Jay Leno]]. In 2011, Chong appeared as a Judge in an episode of ''[[Franklin & Bash]].''\n\nOn September 4, 2014, Chong was announced as one of the celebrities participating on the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 19)|19th season]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''. He paired with professional dancer [[Peta Murgatroyd]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018Dancing With The Stars': Season 19 Celebrity Contestants Revealed|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2014/09/04/dancing-with-the-stars-season-19-cast-dwts-celebrities/|publisher=Hollywood Life}}</ref> Despite being at the bottom of the leaderboard numerous times, Chong and Murgatroyd were able to make it to the night of the semi-finals but were eliminated at the end of that night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-recap-t-55130.aspx|title='Dancing with the Stars' Recap: Top 5 in the Semifinals|access-date=November 17, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121103908/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-recap-t-55130.aspx|archive-date=November 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Chong is the oldest contestant to have made it to the semi-finals of the show.\n\nOn April 4, 2015, Chong appeared as a guest speaker at the annual \"Hash Bash\" event in Ann Arbor, Michigan, which focuses on cannabis legalization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F23Bwk-he8o|title='Hash Bash, 2015'|publisher=GrowGreenerGuru}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Chong guest-starred as himself in an episode of the ''[[Trailer Park Boys]]'' spinoff ''Out of the Park: USA''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5937754/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title='Trailer Park Boys: Out of the Park'|publisher=IMDB}}</ref> In 2017, Chong also partnered with smoking subscription box service Daily High Club to create the DHC Tommy Chong Signature Smoking Supply Box.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.investorideas.com/news/2017/marijuana/11021TommyChong.asp|title='Daily High Club Announces Partnership with Cannabis Culture Legend Tommy Chong'|publisher=Investorideas.com|date=November 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn January 9, 2019 he was revealed at the end of the second episode of ''[[The Masked Singer (U.S. TV series)]]'' to be the singer known as the Pineapple, singing \"[[I Will Survive]]\" by [[Gloria Gaynor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/a25832138/masked-singer-revealed-season-1/|title=Find Out Who Was Unmasked This Week on 'The Masked Singer'|last=Bonner|first=Mehera|date=2019-01-09|website=Cosmopolitan|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 2019, Chong appeared on episode #1303 of the internet video podcast ''[[The Joe Rogan Experience]]'', hosted by [[Joe Rogan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4rHLLmQPqLY|title=Joe Rogan Experience #1303 - Tommy Chong|date=2019-05-23|website=YouTube|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 2019, Chong appeared on episode #694 of the internet video podcast \"The Church Of What's Happening Now\", hosted by [[Joey Diaz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kVwm0uKPRVs|title='TCOWHN: #694 - Tommy Chong'|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Cheech & Chong among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\n===''US vs. Chong''===\nIn 2003 Chong became caught up in two American investigations, code-named [[Operation Pipe Dreams]] and [[Operation Headhunter]], which tried to trace drug traffic and users through businesses selling [[drug paraphernalia]], mostly [[bong]]s.  Operation Pipe Dreams was run from [[Pittsburgh]]. US Attorney for [[Western Pennsylvania]] [[Mary Beth Buchanan]] oversaw the case. The estimated cost of Operation Pipe Dreams was over $12 million and included the resources of 2,000 law enforcement officers.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|first=Steve|last=Mikulan|title=Chong Family Values|date=December 4, 2003|publisher=LA Weekly Times|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/features/chong-family-values/2158/?page=2|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127205521/http://www.laweekly.com/news/features/chong-family-values/2158/?page=2|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 27, 2013}}</ref> Fifty-five companies that sold drug paraphernalia over the Internet were the subject of the investigation, and Nice Dreams was one of them.\n\nChong was charged for his part in financing and promoting Chong Glass/Nice Dreams, a company started by his son Paris. His case never went to trial, as his attorney negotiated a plea agreement with the US Attorney for the Western District of Pennsylvania's Office. He admitted to distributing 7,500 bongs and water pipes on the Internet through Nice Dreams, a family company. Chong agreed to plead guilty to one count of conspiracy to distribute drug paraphernalia in exchange for non-prosecution of his wife, Shelby, and his son, Paris. Chong cooperated with the government and was the first of the Operation Pipe Dreams defendants to plead guilty.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nAt Chong's sentencing, Assistant U.S. Attorney for Western Pennsylvania Mary McKeen Houghton said in her arguments that Tommy Chong \"used his public image to promote this crime\" and marketed his products to children.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">{{cite news |author=Torsten Ove | title=Chong Actor Tommy Chong gets nine months for selling pot pipes| date=September 13, 2003 | newspaper= Pittsburgh Post Gazette| url= http://www.post-gazette.com/localnews/20030912chong0912p5.asp}}</ref> U.S. Attorney [[Mary Beth Buchanan]] also was present at the sentencing in Pittsburgh and released a statement to the press stating, \"there are consequences for violating the law, even if the violator is a well-known entertainer like Thomas Chong.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nWhile Chong argued for community service and home detention at his sentencing, the district judge, [[Arthur J. Schwab]], denied his requests and sentenced him to 9 months in federal prison, a fine of $20,000, forfeiture of $103,514, and the loss of all merchandise seized during the raid of his business.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\" /> Chong served his sentence at the [[Taft Correctional Institution]] from October 8, 2003 to July 7, 2004. He was a cellmate\u2014or \"cubie\"\u2014with \"The Wolf of Wall Street\" [[Jordan Belfort]], and is given credit for encouraging Belfort to write his memoirs. They have remained friends ever since.<ref name=NYMag>{{cite journal|last=Gray|first=Geoffrey|title=The Wolf of Wall Street Can't Sleep|journal=New York|date=December 2, 2013|year=|pages=64\u201369|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/jordan-belfort-2013-12/|accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThese events were among those chronicled in ''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]]'' (2006), a documentary by [[Josh Gilbert (filmmaker)|Josh Gilbert]]. It premiered theatrically at the New York Film Forum in New York City and won awards. His time in prison was also a main point in his book, \"The I Chong\".\n\n===Controversy===\n[[File:Tommy Chong by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|Chong in 2006]]\nWhile government officials denied that Chong was treated any differently from the other defendants, supporters felt his celebrity status was being used against him. Chong's publicist [[Brandie Knight]] said the Chong family was shocked by the raid. \"We've done everything the right way, and the government is saying there is no right way,\" Knight said.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. raids firms selling items used by pot smokers / Ashcroft blames Internet for paraphernalia|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2003-02-25/news/17477256_1_operation-headhunter-head-shops-bongs/2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110301163234/http://articles.sfgate.com/2003-02-25/news/17477256_1_operation-headhunter-head-shops-bongs|archivedate=March 1, 2011| newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref> Supporters started the \"Free Tommy Chong!\" movement that called for his release. They questioned why Chong was prosecuted rather than his son Paris Chong, who was CEO of the business. They also pointed to the disparity in sentences between Chong's and those of other defendants and the DEA tactics used in the investigation.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nParis Chong had started Nice Dreams in 1999. He was never charged with his crimes in relation to the investigation as part of a plea bargain. When asked why the government had focused on Chong rather than his son the CEO, US Attorney Mary Beth Buchanan said that \"Tommy Chong was the more responsible corporate officer because he financed and marketed the product.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nOf the 55 people who were subjects of the investigation, Chong was the only one without previous convictions who received jail time.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> When questioned on the sentencing, U.S. Attorney Mary Beth Buchanan noted that Chong had never gone to trial and made a plea bargain. She said, \"He was a relatively new player, but he had the ability to market products like no other.\"<ref name=\"Tommy Chong's Bongs\">{{cite magazine |author=Greg Beato | title=Tommy Chong's Bongs| date=May 2004 | magazine= Reason Magazine| url= http://www.reason.com/news/show/29137.html}}</ref>\n\nDuring its investigation of Nice Dreams, federal agents posed as head-shop owners from [[Beaver County, Pennsylvania|Beaver County]] in western Pennsylvania. They asked Paris Chong to sell them [[Water pipe percolator|pipes]] through the mail to a fictitious shop in the town of [[Beaver Falls, Pennsylvania|Beaver Falls]], {{convert|31|mi|km}} from Pittsburgh. Paris Chong had been prohibited from selling to Pittsburgh or anywhere in [[Western Pennsylvania]] because of the successful federal prosecution of Akhil Kumar Mishra and his wife, Rajeshwari, who had two head shops in the city.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> Accounts differ as to who in Nice Dreams went against Chong's prohibition, or even if it had been made up by the defense, but the sales did take place to the agents. This enabled the U.S. Attorney to show jurisdiction in Pennsylvania for Chong's illegal activities, as opposed to California, which was the base for Nice Dreams.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n===Aftermath===\nIn December 2004, Chong was to appear in an off-Broadway show entitled ''[[The Marijuana-Logues]]'', a parody of [[Eve Ensler]]'s ''[[The Vagina Monologues]]''. His parole officer barred him from the show and the tour was cancelled, as audience members were smoking pot during performances. Such exposure would cause Chong to violate the terms of his parole.<ref name=\"The Marijuana-Logues up in smoke; Tommy Chong cancels tour'\">{{cite news|author=Jake Coyle|title=\"The Marijuana-Logues\" up in smoke; Tommy Chong cancels tour |date=February 28, 2005 |newspaper=The Seattle Times|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002192319_webchong28.html}}</ref> In 2006, Chong published a memoir about his experiences in jail and his exploration of meditation, called ''The I Chong: Meditations from the Joint''.\n\nIn 2010, Chong and [[Cyril Wecht]] appeared at a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] fundraiser in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]] to aid the campaign against [[Mary Beth Buchanan]], the [[United States Attorney]] who prosecuted him. She was running as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate for the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Roddy |first=Dennis B. |title=Chong and Wecht form an unlikely alliance against Buchanan |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |date=May 6, 2010 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/10126/1056036-53.stm#ixzz0n7uLO400 |accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> She was defeated in the Republican primary.\n\n===Seizure of a/k/a Tommy Chong DVDs===\nOn May 7, 2008, federal agents raided Spectrum Labs in an investigation related to its \"detoxification\" products. The search was one of nine conducted for [[Operation True Test]], an investigation being led by Buchanan, still the U.S. Attorney for the Western District of Pennsylvania. It targeted companies that sell so-called \"masking products,\" intended to help drug-users pass employer drug tests. No federal law bans such products; they are regulated on a state-by-state basis. Of the nine search warrants issued, none was for businesses within Buchanan's district.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news |author=Paula Reed Ward |title=Buchanan picks new target: products that mask drug use |date=May 11, 2008 |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post Gazette |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08132/880918-52.stm}}</ref>\n\nChong claimed that federal agents had seized 8,000\u201310,000 copies of the yet-to-be released documentary, ''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]],'' from Spectrum Labs, but their attorney said no DVDs were taken.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> In a press release, Chong said, \"[The seizure of the DVDs is] a way to punish the distributor financially. There's no way to get the DVDs back until the investigation is over.\" Chong said he did not have any ownership of the film.<ref name=\"raid\">{{cite news| title=Actor Tommy Chong Claims Link to FBI Raids| date=May 8, 2008| publisher=Local 12.com| url=http://www.local12.com/news/local/story.aspx?content_id=06471fa4-66f2-4ffe-8ddf-8c7630326bad| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512153035/http://www.local12.com/news/local/story.aspx?content_id=06471fa4-66f2-4ffe-8ddf-8c7630326bad| archivedate=May 12, 2008| df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' later amended its story, saying that an \"undisclosed number of DVDs was taken\". It noted the government is not required to disclose a reason for the seizure as the raid was part of \"an ongoing investigation\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\n==Reuniting with Cheech==\n[[File:Tommy Chong TIFF08.jpg|thumb|Tommy Chong in Toronto, 2008]]\nChong appeared with his long-time comedy partner, [[Cheech Marin]], in a 2000 [[South Park]] episode called \"[[Cherokee Hair Tampons]]\", where they played fictional versions of themselves.\n\nIn mid-2008, [[Cheech & Chong]] reunited and started touring. The tour was called ''Light Up America and Canada'' and ''The Felimony Tour'', which referred to major expenses of each. In October 2008, they appeared on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'' , the ''[[Opie and Anthony]]'' Show,  and the ''[[Ron and Fez]]'' Show on [[Sirius radio|SIRIUS]]/[[XM Satellite Radio]]. On March 1, 2010, they hosted ''[[WWE Raw]]'' in [[Oklahoma City]]. On March 13, 2011, Cheech & Chong were guest stars on ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[A Midsummer's Nice Dream]]\", where, during a reunion tour, Homer briefly replaced Chong before the pair reconciled.\n\n[[Cheech Marin]] appeared in Tommy Chong's first dance in the season opener of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 19)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', on September 15, 2014. Around this same time, Cheech and Chong appeared together on the internet-based, pro-marijuana show, [[Getting Doug With High]].\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1960, Chong married Maxine Sneed in Canada. She is of [[Black Canadian]] and [[Cherokee]] descent. They have two daughters, [[Rae Dawn Chong|Rae Dawn]] (b. 1961) and [[Robbi Chong]] (b. 1965). They divorced in 1970.\n\nIn 1975, Chong married [[Shelby Chong|Shelby Fiddis]] in Los Angeles. They had three children, sons Paris (b. 1974) and Gilbran (b. 1981), and daughter Precious Chong (b. 1986). In 1978, the couple adopted [[Marcus Chong|Marcus Wyatt]]. Rae Dawn, Robbi, Marcus, Paris, and Precious Chong have each pursued careers in acting. In addition to film work, in May 2011, Precious Chong had her play, ''Push ...One Mother of a Show,'' produced in Toronto.<ref>[http://bunchfamily.ca/precious-chong-pushes-boundaries/ Meghan Housley, \"Precious Chong Pushes Boundaries\"] ''Bunch'', May 7, 2011, accessed December 8, 2013</ref>\n\nIn the late 1980s, Chong became a [[naturalized citizen]] of the United States. Rae Dawn Chong has also become a naturalized U.S. citizen.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\nTommy Chong has become a marijuana activist and supports legalizing the plant's use.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> He is a regular contributor to ''[[Cannabis Culture Magazine]]'' and sits on the [[NORML]] (National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws) advisory board.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://norml.org/advisory-board |title=NORML Advisory Board |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cancer diagnosis===\nChong announced on June 9, 2012, that he is battling [[prostate cancer]]. He described the cancer \"as a slow stage one [that I've] had for a long time.\" He said that he had been drug-free for about three years, during which time he began having prostate-related problems.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comedian Tommy Chong fighting prostate cancer|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/06/09/showbiz/chong-prostate-cancer/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref> On July 15, 2012, Chong tweeted that the [[hemp oil]] treatment he'd been using to cure his cancer was effective and that he is \"99% cancer free.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Twitter|title=Tommy Chong|url=https://twitter.com/tommychong}}</ref> However, on June 16, 2015, Chong stated that he had been diagnosed with [[colorectal cancer]] and was \"using cannabis like crazy\" in order to endure the treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/tommy-chong-i-have-rectal-cancer-2015176 |title=Tommy Chong: \u201cI Got Diagnosed With Rectal Cancer,\u201d in Treatment Now |first=Madeline |last=Boardman |date=June 17, 2015 |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Up in Smoke]]''\n|Anthony \"Man\" Stoner\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Also writer, director\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Cheech & Chong's Next Movie]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Chong\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Nice Dreams]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1982\n|''[[It Came from Hollywood]]''\n|Himself\n|\n|-\n|''[[Things Are Tough All Over]]''\n|Chong / Prince Habib\n|Also writer\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1983\n|''[[Still Smokin (film)|Still Smokin']]''\n|Chong\n|Also writer, director\n|-\n|''[[Yellowbeard]]''\n|El Nebuloso\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Cheech & Chong's The Corsican Brothers]]''\n|Lucian Corsican\n|Also writer, director\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1985\n|''[[Get Out of My Room]]''\n|The Man\n|\n|-\n|''[[After Hours (film)|After Hours]]''\n|Pepe\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Tripwire (film)|Tripwire]]''\n|Merle Shine\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Far Out Man]]''\n|Far Out Man\n|Also writer director\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1992\n|''[[Life After Sex]]''\n|Awkward Naked Guy\n|\n|-\n|''[[FernGully: The Last Rainforest]]''\n|Root\n|[[Voice acting|Voice role]]\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[National Lampoon's Senior Trip]]''\n|Red\n|\n|-\n|1997\n|''[[McHale's Navy]]''\n|Armando / Ernesto\n|\n|-\n|1998\n|''[[Half Baked]]''\n|Squirrel Master\n|\n|-\n|2001\n|''[[The Wash (2001 film)|The Wash]]'' \n|Dee's Connection\n|\n|-\n|2002\n|''[[High Times' Potluck]]'' \n|Himself\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2003\n|''Best Buds''\n|Tommy Chong / Carlos\n|\n|-\n|''[[Pauly Shore Is Dead]]''\n|Himself\n|\n|-\n|2005\n|''Secret Agent 420''\n|QP\n|\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Evil Bong]]''\n|Jimbo Leary\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2007\n|''[[American Drug War: The Last White Hope]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Himself\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Union: The Business Behind Getting High]]''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2008\n|''I Am Somebody: No Chance in Hell''\n|Deputy Tom\n|Original title: ''Chinaman's Chance''\n|-\n|''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]]''\n|Himself\n|DVD release\n|-\n|2010\n|''Cheech & Chong's Hey Watch This''\n|Himself\n|[[Documentary film]]\n|-\n|2011\n|''[[Hoodwinked Too! Hood vs. Evil]]''\n|Stone\n|Voice role\n|-\n|2013\n|''[[Cheech & Chong's Animated Movie]]''\n|Chong\n|Voice role; also writer\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[The Fluffy Movie]]''\n|Video store clerk\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Zootopia]]''\n|Yax \n|Voice role\n|-\n|2017\n|''It's Gawd!''\n|Gawd\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Railroad to Hell: A Chinaman's Chance''\n|Deputy Tom\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Color Out of Space (film)|Color Out of Space]]''\n|Ezra\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Jay and Silent Bob Reboot]]''\n|Alfred\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1986\n|''Playboy Comedy Roast for Tommy Chong''\n|Himself\n|\n|-\n|''[[Miami Vice]]''\n|T.R. \"Jumbo\" Collins\n|Episode: \"Trust Fund Pirates\"\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[The George Carlin Show]]''<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jonathan Aibel |author2=Glenn Berger |author3=Sam Simon |title=\"The George Carlin Show\": George Runs into an Old Friend| date=July 18, 2012| publisher=IMDB|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0587163/}}</ref>\n|Rhodes\n|Episode: \"George Runs Into an Old Friend\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1997\n|''[[Nash Bridges]]''\n|Barry Chen\n|Episode: \"Wild Card\"\n|-\n|''[[Sliders]]''\n|Van Elsinger\n|Episode: \"Stoker\"\n|-\n|1999\n|''[[Dharma & Greg]]''\n|Carl\n|Episode: \"Tie-Dying the Knot\"\n|-\n|1999\u20132006\n|''[[That 70s Show]]''\n|[[Leo (That '70s Show)|Leo Chingkwake]]\n|39 Episodes\n|-\n|2000\n|''[[South Park]]''\n|Chief Running Pinto\n|Episode: \"[[Cherokee Hair Tampons]]\"\n|-\n|2007\n|''[[George Lopez]]'' \n|Mr. Gutierez\n|Episode: \"George Joins the Neighborhood Wha-tcha and Raises the Vigil-ante\"\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Code Monkeys]]''\n|Laird Boony\n|Episode: \"The Secret of 4-20\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2009\n|''[[MADtv]]''\n|rowspan=\"4\"|Himself\n|\n|-\n|''[[Tosh.0]]''\n|Episode: \"Drunk Dunk\"\n|-\n|2010\n|''[[WWE Raw]]''\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2011\n|''[[The Simpsons]]''\n|Episode: \"A Midsummer's Nice Dream\"\n|-\n|''[[Franklin and Bash]]''\n|Judge Tommy Harper\n|Episode: \"The Bangover\"\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2014\n|''[[Raising Hope]]''\n|Hubert Wilson\n|Episode: \"The One Where They Get High\"\n|-\n|''[[The Millers]]''\n|Ganja Pete\n|Episode: \"Bahama Mama\"\n|-\n|''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''\n|Himself/Contestant\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Uncle Grandpa]]''\n|Bottom Bag\n|Episode: \"Bottom Bag\"\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Trailer Park Boys: Out Of the Park: USA]]''\n|Anthony Stoner/Himself\n|Episode: \"Los Angeles 1\"\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[The Masked Singer (U.S. TV series)|The Masked Singer]]''\n|Pineapple/Himself\n|\n|}\n\n===Video games===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Voice role\n! Notes\n|-\n|2006\n|''[[Scarface: The World Is Yours]]''\n|Hippie\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tommy Chong}}\n* {{IMDb name|1045}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050616085333/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/7672769/site/newsweek/ Chong's Bongs Gone Wrong] A Newsweek article by Brian Braiker about Tommy Chong's various legal problems\n* [http://www.hobotrashcan.com/interviews/tommychong.php HoboTrashcan's One on One with Tommy Chong] An in-depth interview about politics, Cheech and Chong and Tommy's wife and kids\n* [http://www.stumpedmagazine.com/interviews/tommy-chong/ An Interview With Tommy Chong] A Stumped? magazine article by Zach Freeman\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090905063448/http://video.msn.com/video.aspx?mkt=en-ca Video interview with Tommy Chong on 'Connected Life']\n*[http://www.law.uga.edu/profile/donald-e-wilkes-jr Donald E. Wilkes, Jr.], [https://web.archive.org/web/20120314091056/http://www.law.uga.edu/dwilkes_more/55pope.html \"Pot Pope Imprisoned.\"] Published in Flagpole Magazine, p.&nbsp;31 (December 20, 2006).\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Cheech & Chong}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chong, Tommy}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:American cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:American male actors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American male comedians]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in the cannabis industry]]\n[[Category:Canadian cannabis activists]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian male actors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian male comedians]]\n[[Category:Canadian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of French descent]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Ulster-Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Psychedelic drug advocates]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Writers from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:People convicted of drug offenses]]\n[[Category:Victoria School of Performing and Visual Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American film directors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Scotch-Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:The Masked Singer (American TV series) contestants]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian-American comedian, actor, and activist}}\n<!--Note:  There is an internet hoax reporting Chong's death.  http://en.mediamass.net/people/tommy-chong/deathhoax.html-->\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name         = Tommy Chong\n| image        = Tommy_Chong_at_Hash_Bash.jpg\n| caption      = Chong in 2015\n| birth_name   = Thomas Bee Kin Chong\n| nationality  = Canadian \u2022 American\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1938|5|24}}  \n| birth_place  = [[Edmonton]], [[Alberta]], Canada\n| medium       = [[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]], [[film]], [[television]]\n| genre        =  [[Observational comedy]], [[stoner comedy]], [[sketch comedy]], [[satire]]\n| subject      = [[Canadian culture]], [[recreational drug use]], [[drug culture]], [[everyday life]]\n| active       = 1962\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Maxine Sneed|1960|1970|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|[[Shelby Chong|Shelby Fiddis]]|1975}}\n| children     = 5, including [[Rae Dawn Chong|Rae Dawn]], [[Robbi Chong|Robbi]]\n}}\n'''Thomas Bing Kin Chong'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://old.post-gazette.com/localnews/20030912chong0912p5.asp |website=Post Gazette |title=Actor Tommy Chong gets nine months for selling pot pipes |date=September 12, 2003 |access-date=August 10, 2016 |last=Ove |first=Torsten |publisher=PG Publishing Co., Inc. |quote=Chong, whose full name is Thomas B. Kin Chong,... |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160716002912/http://old.post-gazette.com/localnews/20030912chong0912p5.asp |archivedate=July 16, 2016 |url-status=live}}</ref> (born May 24, 1938) is a Canadian actor, writer, director, musician, [[cannabis rights]] activist and comedian. He is known for his [[Cannabis (drug)|marijuana]]-themed [[Cheech & Chong]] comedy albums and movies with [[Cheech Marin]], as well as playing the character [[Leo (That '70s Show)|Leo]] on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]'s ''[[That '70s Show]]''. He became a naturalized United States citizen in the late 1980s.\n\n==Early life==\nThomas B. Kin Chong<ref name= \"nardwuar\">{{cite web |date=August 20, 1993|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bGhBodZP1Jw|title=Nardwuar vs. Tommy Chong|work=Nardwuar | via=YouTube |accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cheechandchong.com/biography.html | title= Bio > Tommy Chong| work= CheechandChong.com (official site)| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120213175242/http://www.cheechandchong.com/bio | archivedate= February 13, 2012}} Note: Tommy Chong bio appears under a different person's section, Shelby Chong.</ref> was born on May 24, 1938 at the [[University of Alberta Hospital]] in [[Edmonton]], Alberta.<ref name=filmref /> His mother was Lorna Jean (n\u00e9e Gilchrist),<ref name=\"filmref\">{{cite web | url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/18/Tommy-Chong.html | title=Tommy Chong Biography (1938-)| website= FilmReference.com | accessdate= June 17, 2015}}</ref> a waitress of [[Scottish- Canadians|Scottish-Irish]] ancestry,<ref>{{cite news |title= [Unknown title] |volume= 80 |year=1972 |work= [[Newsweek]] |location=|isbn= |page= |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=d03uAAAAMAAJ&q=TOMMY+CHONG+SCOTCH+FRENCH&dq=TOMMY+CHONG+SCOTCH+FRENCH |accessdate=May 25, 2012}}</ref> and his father was Stanley Chong, a [[Chinese people|Chinese]] truck driver who [[Chinese Canadians|immigrated to Canada]] in the 1930s.<ref name= filmref /><ref name=\"asianweek\"/> After arriving in Canada, the senior Chong had first lived with an aunt in [[Vancouver]], where Chinese immigrants were mostly sequestered in a small area due to racial discrimination.<ref name=\"asianweek\">{{cite news | first=Pratt | last=Paul | title=Growing Up a Chong | date=November 18, 2005 | work=AsianWeek | url=http://www.asianweek.com/2005/11/18/growing-up-a-chong/ | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609190311/http://www.asianweek.com/2005/11/18/growing-up-a-chong/ | archivedate=June 9, 2010 | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=http://norml.org/index.cfm?Group_ID=7072|title= Working to Reform Marijuana Laws | website= NORML.org |publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.yahoo.com/thomas-chong/contributor/264446|title=Tommy Chong|work=Yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\nAs a youth, Tommy Chong moved with his family to [[Calgary]], settling in a conservative neighbourhood Chong has referred to as \"Dog Patch\". He has said that his father had \"been wounded in [[World War II]] and there was a veterans' hospital in Calgary. He bought a $500 house in Dog Patch and raised his family on $50 a week.\"<ref name=\"nardwuar\"/> In an interview, Chong later said:\n{{cquote|I dropped out of [[Crescent Heights High School (Calgary, Alberta)|Crescent Heights High School]] when I was 16 but probably just before they were going to throw me out anyway&nbsp;... I played guitar to make money. I was about 16 when I discovered that music could get you [[sexual intercourse|laid]], even if you were a scrawny, long-haired, geeky-looking guy like me.<ref name=\"nardwuar\"/>}}\n\n==Career==\n===Music===\nBy the early 1960s, Chong was playing guitar for a Calgary soul group called the Shades. The Shades moved to [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], where the band's name changed to \"Little Daddy & the Bachelors\". They recorded a single, \"Too Much Monkey Business\" / \"Junior's Jerk\". Together with bandmember Bobby Taylor, Chong opened a Vancouver nightclub in 1963.  Formerly the Alma Theatre, they called it \"Blue Balls\". They brought in the [[Ike & Tina Turner]] Revue, which had never been to Vancouver before. Although Little Daddy & the Bachelors built up a small following, things soured when they went with Chong's suggestion and had themselves billed as \"Four [[Nigger]]s and a [[Chink]]\"<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|author=Hamilton, Andrew|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/p130602|title=Bobby Taylor|work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref> (or, bowing to pressure, \"Four N's and a C\") before taking on the moniker [[Bobby Taylor & the Vancouvers]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" />\n\nIn 1965, the Vancouvers signed with Gordy Records (a subsidiary of Detroit's [[Motown Records]]). They recorded their debut album, an [[eponymous]] release, and their debut single, the Tommy Chong co-composition, \"Does Your Mama Know About Me,\" which peaked at number 29 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].<ref name=\"allmusic\" /> While on tour in Chicago for a short time, the band followed opening act [[the Jackson 5]]. Chong later referred to the young [[Michael Jackson]] as a \"cute little guy\".<ref name=\"tomgreen.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tomgreen.com/?video=1089|title=Tom Green - The Channel - WebovisionTom Green - The Channel|publisher=}}</ref> After the band released two additional singles, Chong and bandmate Wes Henderson missed a Friday night performance to apply for [[Permanent residence (United States)|green cards]] so they could become American citizens. Chong was fired by [[Chris Clark (singer)|Chris Clark]] and Motown producer [[Johnny Bristol]] for arriving late to the gig. Later, when Berry Gordy told Chong that he wasn't fired after all, that it had been a mistake, Chong said he wanted to stay fired. \"I said I want to become a Berry Gordy, I don't want to just work for a Berry Gordy. And he says I can, I can dig that. So he was nice. He gave me $5,000 as the severance and to me that was a fortune.\" - Tommy Chong. <!--Above material apparently had been copied from article \"Bobby Taylor & the Vancouvers\"--><ref name=\"harp\">{{cite web\n |year=2007 \n |url=http://www.harpmagazine.com/articles/detail.cfm?article_id=6162 \n |last=Kayce \n |first=Aaron \n |title=Tommy Chong: From Guitar to Bong \n |work=Harp \n |publisher=HarpMagazine.com \n |accessdate=September 24, 2007 \n |url-status=bot: unknown \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090425165739/http://www.harpmagazine.com/articles/detail.cfm?article_id=6162 \n |archivedate=April 25, 2009 \n}}</ref> The group broke up shortly afterwards, when Chong tried to reduce the number of players covered by the Vancouvers' contract. He intended that he, Taylor, and Henderson would constitute the group, while other members would be classified as sidemen and session artists.\n\n===Cheech & Chong===\n{{Main|Cheech & Chong}}\nChong co-wrote and performed on many Cheech & Chong comedy albums, four of which were nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Comedy Album]]. He and [[Cheech Marin]] shared the 1973 award in this category for ''[[Los Cochinos]]''.<ref>[https://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=%22cheech+and+chong%22&field_nominee_work_value=&year=All&genre=All Cheech and Chong at grammy.com]</ref>\n\nHe also directed four of the duo's films, while co-writing and starring in all seven with Cheech.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[The New York Times]]|title=Tommy Chong|url=http://movies.nytimes.com/person/683301/Tommy-Chong/filmography}}</ref>\n\n===After Cheech & Chong===\n[[File:Tommy Chong in 2008.jpg|thumb|Chong speaking in San Francisco in 2008.]]\nCheech & Chong, while a very successful comedy act, split in 1985 due to creative differences and Marin's desire to focus on a mainstream acting career. This began a difficult time for Chong. He developed an unsold pilot for CBS called ''The Martinez Family'', which was redeveloped as the 1988 sitcom ''[[Trial and Error (TV series)|Trial and Error]]''.<ref name=\"Irvin2013\">{{cite book|author=Richard Irvin|title=Forgotten Laughs: An Episode Guide to 150 TV Sitcoms You Probably Never Saw|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GqRWDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT276|year=2013|publisher=BearManor Media|pages=276\u2013|id=GGKEY:Y33N3H4NXN4}}</ref> In 1990, he directed, wrote and starred in the movie ''[[Far Out Man]]''. He did not act regularly until filling the recurring role (later a regular role) as the fun-loving, aging hippie \"[[Leo (That '70s Show)|Leo]]\" (similar to his Chong character) on ''[[That '70s Show]]''. Chong was absent during the fifth and sixth seasons of the show as he was serving a brief jail sentence; upon his release, he returned to the series for its final two seasons. He also played a role as a hippie in ''[[Dharma and Greg]]''.\n\nChong was originally going to voice the character of [[Shenzi, Banzai and Ed|Shenzi]], the hyena in the Disney film ''[[The Lion King]]''.{{citation needed| date=May 2018}} Cheech Marin voiced Banzai. (The Shenzi character was changed to a female, and voiced instead by [[Whoopi Goldberg]].) Chong provided the voice of the character Yax in the 2016 Disney film ''[[Zootopia]]''.<ref name=\"USA Today 25 October 2015\">{{cite news | title= J.K. Simmons, Tommy Chong get run of 'Zootopia'|url= https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/10/25/zootopia-jk-simmons-tommy-chong/74369682/| last= Alexander | first= Bryan | date=October 25, 2015| work= USA Today |publisher= [[Gannett Company]]| accessdate= May 9, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2005, ''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]]'' premiered at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]]. The documentary, produced, written and directed by Josh Gilbert, chronicles Chong's comedic and personal history. It includes material related to his prosecution by the [[United States Department of Justice|US Justice Department]] and imprisonment. The project features interviews with Cheech Marin, [[Bill Maher]], [[George Thorogood]], [[Peter Coyote]], [[Lou Adler]], [[Eric Schlosser]] and [[Jay Leno]]. In 2011, Chong appeared as a Judge in an episode of ''[[Franklin & Bash]].''\n\nOn September 4, 2014, Chong was announced as one of the celebrities participating on the [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 19)|19th season]] of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]''. He paired with professional dancer [[Peta Murgatroyd]].<ref>{{cite web|title=\u2018Dancing With The Stars': Season 19 Celebrity Contestants Revealed|url=http://hollywoodlife.com/2014/09/04/dancing-with-the-stars-season-19-cast-dwts-celebrities/|publisher=Hollywood Life}}</ref> Despite being at the bottom of the leaderboard numerous times, Chong and Murgatroyd were able to make it to the night of the semi-finals but were eliminated at the end of that night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-recap-t-55130.aspx|title='Dancing with the Stars' Recap: Top 5 in the Semifinals|access-date=November 17, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121103908/http://www.buddytv.com/articles/dancing-with-the-stars/dancing-with-the-stars-recap-t-55130.aspx|archive-date=November 21, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Chong is the oldest contestant to have made it to the semi-finals of the show.\n\nOn April 4, 2015, Chong appeared as a guest speaker at the annual \"Hash Bash\" event in Ann Arbor, Michigan, which focuses on cannabis legalization.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F23Bwk-he8o|title='Hash Bash, 2015'|publisher=GrowGreenerGuru}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2017, Chong guest-starred as himself in an episode of the ''[[Trailer Park Boys]]'' spinoff ''Out of the Park: USA''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt5937754/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|title='Trailer Park Boys: Out of the Park'|publisher=IMDB}}</ref> In 2017, Chong also partnered with smoking subscription box service Daily High Club to create the DHC Tommy Chong Signature Smoking Supply Box.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.investorideas.com/news/2017/marijuana/11021TommyChong.asp|title='Daily High Club Announces Partnership with Cannabis Culture Legend Tommy Chong'|publisher=Investorideas.com|date=November 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn January 9, 2019 he was revealed at the end of the second episode of ''[[The Masked Singer (U.S. TV series)]]'' to be the singer known as the Pineapple, singing \"[[I Will Survive]]\" by [[Gloria Gaynor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/a25832138/masked-singer-revealed-season-1/|title=Find Out Who Was Unmasked This Week on 'The Masked Singer'|last=Bonner|first=Mehera|date=2019-01-09|website=Cosmopolitan|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref>\n\nOn May 23, 2019, Chong appeared on episode #1303 of the internet video podcast ''[[The Joe Rogan Experience]]'', hosted by [[Joe Rogan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4rHLLmQPqLY|title=Joe Rogan Experience #1303 - Tommy Chong|date=2019-05-23|website=YouTube|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-23}}</ref>\n\nOn June 19, 2019, Chong appeared on episode #694 of the internet video podcast \"The Church Of What's Happening Now\", hosted by [[Joey Diaz]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kVwm0uKPRVs|title='TCOWHN: #694 - Tommy Chong'|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nOn June 25, 2019, ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'' listed Cheech & Chong among hundreds of artists whose material was reportedly destroyed in the [[2008 Universal fire]].<ref name=\"Rosen2\">{{cite web |last1=Rosen |first1=Jody |title=Here Are Hundreds More Artists Whose Tapes Were Destroyed in the UMG Fire |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/magazine/universal-music-fire-bands-list-umg.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=June 28, 2019 |date=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legal issues==\n===''US vs. Chong''===\nIn 2003 Chong became caught up in two American investigations, code-named [[Operation Pipe Dreams]] and [[Operation Headhunter]], which tried to trace drug traffic and users through businesses selling [[drug paraphernalia]], mostly [[bong]]s.  Operation Pipe Dreams was run from [[Pittsburgh]]. US Attorney for [[Western Pennsylvania]] [[Mary Beth Buchanan]] oversaw the case. The estimated cost of Operation Pipe Dreams was over $12 million and included the resources of 2,000 law enforcement officers.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|first=Steve|last=Mikulan|title=Chong Family Values|date=December 4, 2003|publisher=LA Weekly Times|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/features/chong-family-values/2158/?page=2|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130127205521/http://www.laweekly.com/news/features/chong-family-values/2158/?page=2|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 27, 2013}}</ref> Fifty-five companies that sold drug paraphernalia over the Internet were the subject of the investigation, and Nice Dreams was one of them.\n\nChong was charged for his part in financing and promoting Chong Glass/Nice Dreams, a company started by his son Paris. His case never went to trial, as his attorney negotiated a plea agreement with the US Attorney for the Western District of Pennsylvania's Office. He admitted to distributing 7,500 bongs and water pipes on the Internet through Nice Dreams, a family company. Chong agreed to plead guilty to one count of conspiracy to distribute drug paraphernalia in exchange for non-prosecution of his wife, Shelby, and his son, Paris. Chong cooperated with the government and was the first of the Operation Pipe Dreams defendants to plead guilty.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nAt Chong's sentencing, Assistant U.S. Attorney for Western Pennsylvania Mary McKeen Houghton said in her arguments that Tommy Chong \"used his public image to promote this crime\" and marketed his products to children.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">{{cite news |author=Torsten Ove | title=Chong Actor Tommy Chong gets nine months for selling pot pipes| date=September 13, 2003 | newspaper= Pittsburgh Post Gazette| url= http://www.post-gazette.com/localnews/20030912chong0912p5.asp}}</ref> U.S. Attorney [[Mary Beth Buchanan]] also was present at the sentencing in Pittsburgh and released a statement to the press stating, \"there are consequences for violating the law, even if the violator is a well-known entertainer like Thomas Chong.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nWhile Chong argued for community service and home detention at his sentencing, the district judge, [[Arthur J. Schwab]], denied his requests and sentenced him to 9 months in federal prison, a fine of $20,000, forfeiture of $103,514, and the loss of all merchandise seized during the raid of his business.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\" /> Chong served his sentence at the [[Taft Correctional Institution]] from October 8, 2003 to July 7, 2004. He was a cellmate\u2014or \"cubie\"\u2014with \"The Wolf of Wall Street\" [[Jordan Belfort]], and is given credit for encouraging Belfort to write his memoirs. They have remained friends ever since.<ref name=NYMag>{{cite journal|last=Gray|first=Geoffrey|title=The Wolf of Wall Street Can't Sleep|journal=New York|date=December 2, 2013|year=|pages=64\u201369|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/jordan-belfort-2013-12/|accessdate=December 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThese events were among those chronicled in ''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]]'' (2006), a documentary by [[Josh Gilbert (filmmaker)|Josh Gilbert]]. It premiered theatrically at the New York Film Forum in New York City and won awards. His time in prison was also a main point in his book, \"The I Chong\".\n\n===Controversy===\n[[File:Tommy Chong by David Shankbone.jpg|thumb|Chong in 2006]]\nWhile government officials denied that Chong was treated any differently from the other defendants, supporters felt his celebrity status was being used against him. Chong's publicist [[Brandie Knight]] said the Chong family was shocked by the raid. \"We've done everything the right way, and the government is saying there is no right way,\" Knight said.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. raids firms selling items used by pot smokers / Ashcroft blames Internet for paraphernalia|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2003-02-25/news/17477256_1_operation-headhunter-head-shops-bongs/2|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110301163234/http://articles.sfgate.com/2003-02-25/news/17477256_1_operation-headhunter-head-shops-bongs|archivedate=March 1, 2011| newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref> Supporters started the \"Free Tommy Chong!\" movement that called for his release. They questioned why Chong was prosecuted rather than his son Paris Chong, who was CEO of the business. They also pointed to the disparity in sentences between Chong's and those of other defendants and the DEA tactics used in the investigation.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nParis Chong had started Nice Dreams in 1999. He was never charged with his crimes in relation to the investigation as part of a plea bargain. When asked why the government had focused on Chong rather than his son the CEO, US Attorney Mary Beth Buchanan said that \"Tommy Chong was the more responsible corporate officer because he financed and marketed the product.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\nOf the 55 people who were subjects of the investigation, Chong was the only one without previous convictions who received jail time.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> When questioned on the sentencing, U.S. Attorney Mary Beth Buchanan noted that Chong had never gone to trial and made a plea bargain. She said, \"He was a relatively new player, but he had the ability to market products like no other.\"<ref name=\"Tommy Chong's Bongs\">{{cite magazine |author=Greg Beato | title=Tommy Chong's Bongs| date=May 2004 | magazine= Reason Magazine| url= http://www.reason.com/news/show/29137.html}}</ref>\n\nDuring its investigation of Nice Dreams, federal agents posed as head-shop owners from [[Beaver County, Pennsylvania|Beaver County]] in western Pennsylvania. They asked Paris Chong to sell them [[Water pipe percolator|pipes]] through the mail to a fictitious shop in the town of [[Beaver Falls, Pennsylvania|Beaver Falls]], {{convert|31|mi|km}} from Pittsburgh. Paris Chong had been prohibited from selling to Pittsburgh or anywhere in [[Western Pennsylvania]] because of the successful federal prosecution of Akhil Kumar Mishra and his wife, Rajeshwari, who had two head shops in the city.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> Accounts differ as to who in Nice Dreams went against Chong's prohibition, or even if it had been made up by the defense, but the sales did take place to the agents. This enabled the U.S. Attorney to show jurisdiction in Pennsylvania for Chong's illegal activities, as opposed to California, which was the base for Nice Dreams.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n===Aftermath===\nIn December 2004, Chong was to appear in an off-Broadway show entitled ''[[The Marijuana-Logues]]'', a parody of [[Eve Ensler]]'s ''[[The Vagina Monologues]]''. His parole officer barred him from the show and the tour was cancelled, as audience members were smoking pot during performances. Such exposure would cause Chong to violate the terms of his parole.<ref name=\"The Marijuana-Logues up in smoke; Tommy Chong cancels tour'\">{{cite news|author=Jake Coyle|title=\"The Marijuana-Logues\" up in smoke; Tommy Chong cancels tour |date=February 28, 2005 |newspaper=The Seattle Times|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002192319_webchong28.html}}</ref> In 2006, Chong published a memoir about his experiences in jail and his exploration of meditation, called ''The I Chong: Meditations from the Joint''.\n\nIn 2010, Chong and [[Cyril Wecht]] appeared at a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] fundraiser in [[Pittsburgh]], [[Pennsylvania]] to aid the campaign against [[Mary Beth Buchanan]], the [[United States Attorney]] who prosecuted him. She was running as a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate for the [[United States House of Representatives]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Roddy |first=Dennis B. |title=Chong and Wecht form an unlikely alliance against Buchanan |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |date=May 6, 2010 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/10126/1056036-53.stm#ixzz0n7uLO400 |accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> She was defeated in the Republican primary.\n\n===Seizure of a/k/a Tommy Chong DVDs===\nOn May 7, 2008, federal agents raided Spectrum Labs in an investigation related to its \"detoxification\" products. The search was one of nine conducted for [[Operation True Test]], an investigation being led by Buchanan, still the U.S. Attorney for the Western District of Pennsylvania. It targeted companies that sell so-called \"masking products,\" intended to help drug-users pass employer drug tests. No federal law bans such products; they are regulated on a state-by-state basis. Of the nine search warrants issued, none was for businesses within Buchanan's district.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite news |author=Paula Reed Ward |title=Buchanan picks new target: products that mask drug use |date=May 11, 2008 |newspaper=Pittsburgh Post Gazette |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08132/880918-52.stm}}</ref>\n\nChong claimed that federal agents had seized 8,000\u201310,000 copies of the yet-to-be released documentary, ''[[a/k/a Tommy Chong]],'' from Spectrum Labs, but their attorney said no DVDs were taken.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> In a press release, Chong said, \"[The seizure of the DVDs is] a way to punish the distributor financially. There's no way to get the DVDs back until the investigation is over.\" Chong said he did not have any ownership of the film.<ref name=\"raid\">{{cite news| title=Actor Tommy Chong Claims Link to FBI Raids| date=May 8, 2008| publisher=Local 12.com| url=http://www.local12.com/news/local/story.aspx?content_id=06471fa4-66f2-4ffe-8ddf-8c7630326bad| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512153035/http://www.local12.com/news/local/story.aspx?content_id=06471fa4-66f2-4ffe-8ddf-8c7630326bad| archivedate=May 12, 2008| df=mdy-all}}</ref> The ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' later amended its story, saying that an \"undisclosed number of DVDs was taken\". It noted the government is not required to disclose a reason for the seizure as the raid was part of \"an ongoing investigation\".<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\n==Reuniting with Cheech==\n[[File:Tommy Chong TIFF08.jpg|thumb|Tommy Chong in Toronto, 2008]]\nChong appeared with his long-time comedy partner, [[Cheech Marin]], in a 2000 [[South Park]] episode called \"[[Cherokee Hair Tampons]]\", where they played fictional versions of themselves.\n\nIn mid-2008, [[Cheech & Chong]] reunited and started touring. The tour was called ''Light Up America and Canada'' and ''The Felimony Tour'', which referred to major expenses of each. In October 2008, they appeared on ''[[The Howard Stern Show]]'' , the ''[[Opie and Anthony]]'' Show,  and the ''[[Ron and Fez]]'' Show on [[Sirius radio|SIRIUS]]/[[XM Satellite Radio]]. On March 1, 2010, they hosted ''[[WWE Raw]]'' in [[Oklahoma City]]. On March 13, 2011, Cheech & Chong were guest stars on ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[A Midsummer's Nice Dream]]\", where, during a reunion tour, Homer briefly replaced Chong before the pair reconciled.\n\n[[Cheech Marin]] appeared in Tommy Chong's first dance in the season opener of ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 19)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', on September 15, 2014. Around this same time, Cheech and Chong appeared together on the internet-based, pro-marijuana show, [[Getting Doug With High]].\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1960, Chong married Maxine Sneed in Canada. She is of [[Black Canadian]] and [[Cherokee]] descent. They have two daughters, [[Rae Dawn Chong|Rae Dawn]] (b. 1961) and [[Robbi Chong]] (b. 1965). They divorced in 1970.\n\nIn 1975, Chong married [[Shelby Chong|Shelby Fiddis]] in Los Angeles. They had three children, sons Paris (b. 1974) and Gilbran (b. 1981), and daughter Precious Chong (b. 1968). In 1978, the couple adopted [[Marcus Chong|Marcus Wyatt]]. Rae Dawn, Robbi, Marcus, Paris, and Precious Chong have each pursued careers in acting. In addition to film work, in May 2011, Precious Chong had her play, ''Push ...One Mother of a Show,'' produced in Toronto.<ref>[http://bunchfamily.ca/precious-chong-pushes-boundaries/ Meghan Housley, \"Precious Chong Pushes Boundaries\"] ''Bunch'', May 7, 2011, accessed December 8, 2013</ref>\n\nIn the late 1980s, Chong became a [[naturalized citizen]] of the United States. Rae Dawn Chong has also become a naturalized U.S. citizen.{{citation needed|date=September 2016}}\n\nTommy Chong has become a marijuana activist and supports legalizing the plant's use.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> He is a regular contributor to ''[[Cannabis Culture Magazine]]'' and sits on the [[NORML]] (National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws) advisory board.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://norml.org/advisory-board |title=NORML Advisory Board |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cancer diagnosis===\nChong announced on June 9, 2012, that he is battling [[prostate cancer]]. He described the cancer \"as a slow stage one [that I've] had for a long time.\" He said that he had been drug-free for about three years, during which time he began having prostate-related problems.<ref>{{cite news|title=Comedian Tommy Chong fighting prostate cancer|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/06/09/showbiz/chong-prostate-cancer/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=June 10, 2012}}</ref> On July 15, 2012, Chong tweeted that the [[hemp oil]] treatment he'd been using to cure his cancer was effective and that he is \"99% cancer free.\"<ref>{{cite web|work=Twitter|title=Tommy Chong|url=https://twitter.com/tommychong}}</ref> However, on June 16, 2015, Chong stated that he had been diagnosed with [[colorectal cancer]] and was \"using cannabis like crazy\" in order to endure the treatment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usmagazine.com/celebrity-news/news/tommy-chong-i-have-rectal-cancer-2015176 |title=Tommy Chong: \u201cI Got Diagnosed With Rectal Cancer,\u201d in Treatment Now |first=Madeline |last=Boardman |date=June 17, 2015 |access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Up in Smoke]]''\n|Anthony \"Man\" Stoner\n|rowspan=\"3\"|Also writer, director\n|-\n|1980\n|''[[Cheech & Chong's Next Movie]]''\n|rowspan=\"2\"| Chong\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Nice Dreams]]''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1982\n|''[[It Came from Hollywood]]''\n|Himself\n|\n|-\n|''[[Things Are Tough All Over]]''\n|Chong / Prince Habib\n|Also writer\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1983\n|''[[Still Smokin (film)|Still Smokin']]''\n|Chong\n|Also writer, director\n|-\n|''[[Yellowbeard]]''\n|El Nebuloso\n|\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Cheech & Chong's The Corsican Brothers]]''\n|Lucian Corsican\n|Also writer, director\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1985\n|''[[Get Out of My Room]]''\n|The Man\n|\n|-\n|''[[After Hours (film)|After Hours]]''\n|Pepe\n|\n|-\n|1989\n|''[[Tripwire (film)|Tripwire]]''\n|Merle Shine\n|\n|-\n|1990\n|''[[Far Out Man]]''\n